I have nothing against a nice Shakespearean phrasing, but the clue should match it in some way.

@Dc

I'm not a musician, but as I understand it, if you're playing, for example, in the key of C sharp, the notes are C#, D#, E#, F#, G#, A#, B#.  B# is equivalent to C, and E# is equivalent to F, but if we used C and F, there would be two notes on the C and E lines, and the B and E lines would go unused.  Thus, C and F are called B# and E#, respectively for that key.

So I don't see what the issue is with the clue.

